Tangier,wJhvcmFMpwY,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg.95N0hoQ2JXB9S8OG-ns0aK,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg,@timothya2742,Met them in Scranton PA. Doing a show in the park next to the hospital. It was pouring rain and they were getting soaked. Still played on. Invited them back to our band room to just hang. They had few local fans at the time and we had beer and women and a dry stage to jam on. That's all I'm gonna say bout that except that I liked Cinderella better,2021-09-11T05:42:49Z,2021-09-11T05:42:49Z,1,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:07.838442
Tangier,wJhvcmFMpwY,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg.95N0hoQ2JXB9ZO3OC62l7q,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg,@rotadymaify,"@nathanlansford1882 80’s rock were the masters of musicianship. Big melody vocals and hooks, screaming guitar solos, big production and actually putting on a show for their fans. Great stage presence. Not like the bull shit that poisoned the music scene in the 90’s. Flannel shirts, greasy hair, singing about suicide, no melody to the music and no guitar solos. No wonder grunge only lasted a few years. It sucked.",2022-03-10T07:28:02Z,2022-03-10T07:28:02Z,8,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:07.838447
Tangier,wJhvcmFMpwY,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg.95N0hoQ2JXB9ZTM2bUKlKW,UgzbYNj9p9pLY4XXxi94AaABAg,@nathanlansford1882,"Plenty of people wanted it though, by that point. They were sick of hundreds of pop-glam metal bands doing the same types of songs with the same types of lyrics all the time. 

From 1988 to '91, that was increasingly the case. And it wasn't only the grunge fans that felt that way about it--so did the underground speed/thrash, death/grindcore & black metal fans (& bands).",2022-03-12T08:47:19Z,2022-03-12T08:47:19Z,1,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:07.838453
