Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgzyLAPRLWk-BQyAPxZ4AaABAg,,@Nella2025,"Totally disagree with the 'These nine countries' writer's assertion that Canada ( i.e. gov't) restricts our people from visiting the US. This statement is not true. Canadian citizens make these decisions individually and voluntarily (also includes purchasing power of goods and services) on a grassroots level. I, one of numerous others, am truly sick of the widespread US arrogance toward Canada. For me, this goes way back to the late 1950s. Given the choice, my dollar goes to non-US sources wherever possible, including my cancellation of a trip to Hawaii. The 52st state rhetoric has only accelerated Canadian citizens' spending decisions. US gov't and businesses can continue to insist that we take their liquor (or travel there) but stocking the shelves just wastes provincial shelf space when there are very few buyers of US sourced goods and lots of Canadian and international optiions.",2026-04-25T09:00:58Z,2026-04-25T09:08:38Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-26T09:53:14.277204
Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgxugnKfnFybuRnX1xJ4AaABAg,,@alaindumont1872,"in 2009 I spent 5 months in Metz, They say that France's welcome is chilly> I always wore my pin that said Canada. The welcome I received from the epople was genuinely warm and friendly. At the grocery store, people would go out of their way to come and greet me and offer assistance if I needed.often, I would llok out for oncoming car, in the middle of intersections and car would stop and give me a friendly signal to go ahead and cross. I have never forgotten how nice people there were.",2026-04-25T08:55:18Z,2026-04-25T08:55:18Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-26T09:53:14.277211
Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgxMTnMfrsdF3aRjG8B4AaABAg,,@babavee100,"I am English and have lived in France for 30 years. The French are not unfriendly. How could a country that prizes good food and wine be anything else but convivial. I think it comes from the fact that most folks can't speak French. The occasional blank stare which you may encounter, is simply that they don't know what you are saying. The fact that you don't know what they are saying is no excuse. It is France, try to learn a few words such as please and thank you. The French are extremely polite and the fact you don't say merci or bonjour  can be interpreted as deliberately rude.    
Once you understand that asking  directions from a person with a cigarette hanging out of their mouth, odour of garlic and wine on their breath, and their gesticulations taking up most of the space around them, it isn't aggression... She is just trying to be helpful.",2026-04-25T08:01:39Z,2026-04-25T08:01:39Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-26T09:53:14.277217
