Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,Ugzh_7RgNZgAuP1Qrj54AaABAg,,@aGhostlight,"For the Netherlands: the GENERAL anti-tourist sentiment is specifically Amsterdam, which does have a huge overtourism problem, to the point where a lot of Dutch people choose different cities to go to over Amsterdam (Utrecht, Haarlem, Rotterdam, and here in the North, even Alkmaar is preferred over Amsterdam). But it's all relative. 

Where I'm from, we see a huge influx of Germans every summer, and enough Germans here throughout the year as well, due to our proximity to the beach, dunes, and harbour. Most people in my city do NOT like German tourists for the same reason as the rest of the world do not like American tourists: they're entitled, refuse to speak anything but German and expect us to address them solely in German (calling us stupid if we can only address them in English), they don't respect our traffic laws and instead just interact with traffic as though they're in Germany (stopping in the middle of a roundabout for bikers, or just crossing roads on their bikes ignoring the signs on the road telling them they don't have right of way, and then getting angry when they get hit by a car for their reckless cycling), and the general regard of locals as ""lesser"" than them. 

A Belgium tourist, or an Austrian tourist, or even French tourists, when we have them here, they don't meet that same animosity as German tourists. So outside of Amsterdam, I think Canadian tourists would be quite welcomed. Every Dutch person would honestly recommend you go to other cities anyway, since due to the overtourism, Amsterdam is barely even a Dutch city anymore. The primary spoke language, even in customer-forward industries like retail and the restaurant business, is English. You won't even get all that far anymore speaking only Dutch in Amsterdam, and that adds to the anti-tourist sentiment in the city. 

If you come to the Netherlands, I highly suggest you visit places like Utrecht, Haarlem, Leeuwarden, Rotterdam, Groningen, even Eindhoven instead. Or, if you're a big fan of theme parks, plan a trip around De Efteling. Every tourist there is welcomed with full hospitality, as the Dutch are incredibly proud of that theme park, and its employees are wholly enthusiastic to share their love of it with foreigners.",2026-04-24T10:39:51Z,2026-04-24T10:39:51Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-26T09:53:14.277477
Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,Ugw-FA37UFt6A73V8XF4AaABAg,,@statostheman,"I reside in the northern part of Stockholm, Sweden. During my teenage years, I frequently commuted to Stockholm. I would simply purchase some clothing from my favorite store. It was not a long walk from the central station. That day was bustling with people. As I crossed the crosswalk, I accidentally bumped into an older American woman. I apologized in Swedish (not realizing she was American) and continued on my way. 

She began to scream that I had assaulted her and demanded my personal information so she could sue me. I refused. Then she approached two police officers and drew their attention. Tensions were high. Eventually, the officers had had enough of this woman and informed her that if she did not leave the area, she would be arrested. I felt so surreal after that.",2026-04-24T10:12:08Z,2026-04-24T10:12:08Z,0,False,0.0,2026-04-26T09:53:14.277482
