Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg.AVpR0HbDbu2AVpZhH6tXes,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg,@babel2675,"Portugal here. Most Portuguese see Americans as cognitively impaired in some way or another. I went to see the American electronic duo, Matmos, at a venue in my suburban hometown. Same-sex marriage had very recently been legalized in the US. Matmos stopped the show and asked about the crowd's reaction to that. They asked whether people were dancing in the streets. They had no idea Portugal legalized same-sex marriage years before the US. The crowd answered them with a cold, sepulchral silence. This made them quite unhappy. They asked whether anyone in the audience was gay, and wouldn't continue the performance until somebody, anybody, answered them. Now, this is heartland Portugal, very conservative, and being gay carries social stigma (it shouldn't, but does). We all sat in silence for minutes. Finally, a kid at the back of the room yelled, ""I think I might be gay."" When he did, one of the musicians proceeded to lecture us all on how gay people have contributed to civilization. He mentioned Alan Turing, among others. Only then, when he had expressed his... moral outrage, did the show resume. 

So basically Matmos acted as tourists. They came to a country they knew nothing about, assumed our laws had to catch up to theirs, rather than the other way around, and instantly got on the high horse of American exceptionalism when reality failed to assuage their preconceptions. This was about 10 years ago.",2026-04-20T16:32:47Z,2026-04-20T16:32:47Z,30,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:14.675614
Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg.AVpR0HbDbu2AVpZzyIvnan,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg,@markopecinovic4475,"Lived everywhere in the world....4 continents, 70+ countries visited. 

