Tourism,cSHqVU3-DgA,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg.AVpR0HbDbu2AVpz-W9y4Jg,UgxTYdKd_ZO1iGoT1uJ4AaABAg,@lohikarhu734,"@streetstroller;
If you think that GTL is cherry-pickin, you'd be kind of stretching it...The difference among tourists from, say, Canada, is immense, and pretty evident. I've been traveling outside Canada on business, and touring, and the fact is that US tourists are usually ignorant of the countries they are visiting, because they simply aren't exposed to news stories, or the history, about Europe and Asia, and even Canada! American tourist in Toronto asks which bus to catch to visit Vancouver for a day... I met a US soldier in an Imbiss in München, 1979, and asked him what he thought about Munich; his answer:""It's kind of like Chicago..""
I responded:""True. There are cars on the street, people walking around, big buildings...""
There are some US tourists who try to be nice, but, again, they often show how little they know, and the amount that they really don't ""get"", because of their ignorance of the world; it's often not ""dumb"", but the complete lack of awareness of the rest of the world, the ""ignorance"", makes them say dumb things, make assumptions about laws and culture, because Americans are inculcated with the sense that nothing outside the USA is important, or worth learning about, except, in good cases, where they have at least read a guide book... Sadly, most guide books can't replace the years of missing information, misinformation, and outright propaganda about the USA's ""greatness"" and influence.
Sorry to rattle on, but it's that lack of knowledge, even lack of interest, that ""snags"" many US Americans (BTW: even calling yourself ""American"" is another case of appropriating ""American"" away from all of the other countries on the American continents! )",2026-04-20T20:22:36Z,2026-04-20T20:22:36Z,10,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:14.675809
