In Japan and across Europe, the loudest, most demanding, most arrogant people I've come across have been either American or mainland Chinese.

I was on a train in Tokyo last year with an American couple nearby talking loudly enough for everyone else in the train car to hear everything they were saying. One of the pair was standing, the other sitting. There were plenty of open seats for them to sit next to each other and talk quietly to each other. They refused to and insisted on being as loud as they could.
People are expected to be quiet on public transport. You're expected to not talk on phones (unless on a shinkansen and on the train deck by the exit doors) and are expected to turn phones off entirely when near the priority seating areas.
I was tempted to lean over to the American couple and mention if they sat down next to each other, they could talk quietly and not disturb everyone else on the train, but refrained as that would have likely started an augment. I looked at the Japanese man sitting across from me, we both glanced at the Americans and rolled our eyes.

On a recent trip, I was having dinner with an American and a German. The topic of American politics came up. When I mentioned that the entire world hates the US for what they've been doing (this was 2 weeks before the whole Iran thing started) and used the 51st state thing as an example, the American said that people have been saying that about Canada before Trump and it was just a joke. He was confused when I pointed out that no one else sees it as a joke and finds it threatening.",2026-04-21T01:24:13Z,2026-04-21T01:24:13Z,9,True,,2026-04-26T09:53:14.675885
